<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: STAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Critics Take Stand on Censorship: Members of the American Theatre Critics Assn. 
voted Monday to urge Congress to continue funding the National Endowment for 
the Arts without restricting the content of artistic expression. The ATCA, the 
only national organization of drama critics in the United States, issued a 
statement saying: "The American Theatre Critics Assn. strongly urges Congress 
to reauthorize the National Endowment for the Arts without restrictions on 
artistic content leaving its traditional fiscal and evaluative structure 
intact, so that creativity can continue to flourish in the United States." The 
statement was passed unanimously by theater critics attending the national 
convention of the ATCA held in Pittsfield, Mass. ATCA membership includes 
nearly 300 newspaper, magazine, television and radio critics throughout the 
U.S. GREG BRAXTON 
</P>
