<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOP AIR POLLUTION PENALTIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The South Coast Air Quality Management District has responsibility to control 
air pollution. It can seek court-imposed fines against polluters of from $25 to 
$25,000 a day based on such factors as the extent that emissions exceed legal 
limits, potential danger to the public, whether the violation was intentional, 
accidental or due to negligence and the company's history of violations. These 
are the 10 top penalties in May: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
COMPANY 
</P>
<P>
Somitex Prints of California Industry 
</P>
<P>
TYPE OF BUSINESS 
</P>
<P>
Polyester fabrics printer 
</P>
<P>
PENALTY 
</P>
<P>
$50,000 
</P>
<P>
VIOLATION 
</P>
<P>
Re-routing duct work without a permit; operating equipment contrary to permit 
conditions; excessive hydrocarbons from dyeing process; excessive visible 
emissions. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
COMPANY 
</P>
<P>
R.D. Builders Orange, and Groundwater Technology Torrance 
</P>
<P>
TYPE OF BUSINESS 
</P>
<P>
General contractor for excavating underground gasoline storage tanks; soil 
monitoring and sampling firm 
</P>
<P>
PENALTY 
</P>
<P>
$15,500 
</P>
<P>
VIOLATION 
</P>
<P>
Failure to notify the AQMD within 24 hours of detection of 
gasoline-contaminated soil at a Tarzana site; failure to: properly monitor 
excavated soil for gasoline contamination, cover contaminated soil, implement 
mitigation measures and comply with permit conditions. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
COMPANY 
</P>
<P>
ARCO Petroleum Products Co. Carson 
</P>
<P>
TYPE OF BUSINESS 
</P>
<P>
Oil refinery 
</P>
<P>
PENALTY 
</P>
<P>
$13,800 
</P>
<P>
VIOLATION 
</P>
<P>
Vapor recovery compressor breakdown; vapor leaks at butane loading stations; 
excessive hydrocarbons and visible emissions; operating a gasoline storage tank 
contrary to permit conditions. 
