<HEADLINE>
<P>
RAIDERS; 
</P>
<P>
HOLDOUT ENDS FOR NO. 1 PICK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS BAKER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
OXNARD 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After signing a long-term contract, Anthony Smith, the Raiders' No. 1 draft 
pick, arrived at training camp Monday and pulled aside Coach Art Shell. 
</P>
<P>
"He wanted to apologize for being late," Shell said of the defensive end who 
ended a weeklong holdout. "But I told him that we're just happy to have him 
here and we want to just move forward." 
</P>
<P>
Said Smith: "Any time a guy's not here he's going to fall behind. But I'll make 
it back up." He practiced for the first time Monday. 
</P>
<P>
The Raiders have high expectations for Smith, the 11th player selected in the 
draft. A 6-foot-3, 265-pound All-Pacific 10 Conference selection from Arizona, 
Smith was one of the best pass rushers in college football last season. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't have to prove anything," Smith said. "Al Davis drafted me because he 
has confidence in my ability and my skills as a football player. That's all." 
</P>
<P>
The Raiders hope to move Smith into the lineup slowly. He is projected as the 
backup to Scott Davis at left end, and he might play tackle when the Raiders 
employ an extra pass rusher. 
</P>
<P>
"Smith was one of the best pass rushers in this draft," Shell said. "He's very 
explosive and has the ability to come off the corner and rush the passer and 
play the run." 
</P>
<P>
Raider Notes 
</P>
<P>
Jay Lawrence, who covers the Raiders for the Orange County Register, was banned 
Monday from watching the team practice because he has accepted a job covering 
the Denver Broncos at a Denver newspaper, the Rocky Mountain News. The Raiders 
apparently feared Lawrence, who will continue to work for the Register until he 
switches jobs next month, might give away secrets. Lawrence will be allowed to 
interview players and attend Coach Art Shell's daily press conference. "It 
seems a little ridiculous," Lawrence said. "I'm certainly not going to go 
running to anyone with the Denver Broncos and tell them what I've seen here." 
Mark Tomaszewski, Register sports editor, called Raider executive John Herrera 
to ask for an explanation. "(Herrera) said they're treating Jay as an 
out-of-town reporter, and he's just following orders that Al Davis gave him," 
Tomaszewski said. Herrera refused comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
FOOTBALL PLAYERS -- CONTRACTS; LOS ANGELES RAIDERS (FOOTBALL TEAM); SMITH, 
ANTHONY 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
