<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: GENEVA; 
</P>
<P>
THE OIL ANTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The fractious membership of OPEC, the world's most exclusive oil club, will 
take up the question of house rules when the ministers meet in their favorite 
Swiss city this week. 
</P>
<P>
On the table will be a raise in the target price that the 13 member nations 
charge for a barrel of benchmark oil from $18 to $20. Iran, citing recent 
pledges by Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates to stay within their assigned 
production quotas, thinks the time is ripe for such an increase. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iraq is making thinly veiled threats against Kuwait if it violates 
quotas that come out of the Geneva meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
OPEC; OIL PRICES; IRAN -- FOREIGN RELATIONS -- KUWAIT 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
