</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
T-Bill Rates Drop: The Treasury sold $9 billion of new three-month bills at an 
average discount rate of 7.49%, down from 7.62% last week. 
</P>
<P>
Another $9 billion of new six-month bills were sold at an average discount rate 
of 7.40%, down from 7.52% last week. The rates were the lowest since 
three-month bills sold for 7.37% on Oct. 16, 1989, and six-month bills averaged 
7.30% on Dec. 4, 1989. The new discount rates understate the actual return to 
investors -- 7.74% for three-month bills, with a $10,000 bill selling for 
$9,810.70, and 7.79% for a six-month bill selling for $9,625.90. The discount 
rate reflects the price discount received when government securities are 
purchased at less than face value. 
</P>
