Chevron to Sell Mineral Assets: The San Francisco-based oil company said it 
would take a $30-million charge against second-quarter earnings to sell a 
number of mineral assets and restructure its Chevron Resources Co. subsidiary. 
In a "fundamental shift" in strategy, Chevron said it would sell all but three 
major non-coal minerals projects -- a platinum and palladium mine in Montana, a 
copper and silver property in Chile, and zinc and lead deposits in Ireland. 
Chevron Resources will oversee the sale of other minerals assets, which are 
expected to fetch more than $70 million before taxes and result in a net loss. 
