<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: HUNTINGTON BEACH; 
</P>
<P>
POOL TIMING SYSTEM DONATED TO COLLEGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A private swim club has given Golden West College a new timing system for its 
Olympic-size pool. 
</P>
<P>
The community college announced that the private Golden West Swim Club had 
purchased the $3,000 system for the pool. 
</P>
<P>
It has been installed in time for use at the Long Course Junior Olympic 
Regional Competition, which begins Saturday at the college. 
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Ken Hamdorf, swim and water polo coach at Golden West, praised the 
donation and said it is a valuable tool for all competitive swimming events. 
</P>
<P>
"The swimmer comes in and touches the electric pad, and this then goes to the 
computer, which records the exact time," Hamdorf said. "It eliminates a lot of 
people having to hand-time events, and it gets rid of a lot of headaches." 
</P>
<P>
Hamdorf said the electric pads are at the ends of swim lanes in the pool. The 
pads are covered with a rubberized fabric, and the timer is triggered by a 
touch from any part of the swimmer's body. 
</P>
<P>
The Golden West Swim Club comprises about 300 swimmers ranging in age from 4 to 
81. 
</P>
</TEXT>
