<P>
A COMPANY CHRONOLOGY 
</P>
<P>
1956: Ford acquires a defense and development group called Systems Research 
Corp. and renames it Aeronutronic Systems Inc. 
</P>
<P>
1960: Aeronutronic moves to Newport Beach. 
</P>
<P>
1961: Ford acquires Philco Corp., a defense contractor involved in missile 
development and, though its Western Development Laboratories, space systems. 
</P>
<P>
1962: Aeronutronic becomes a division of Philco. 
</P>
<P>
1963: Western Development Laboratories selected to build a mission control 
center for Johnson Space Center. 
</P>
<P>
1965: Chapparal surface-to-air missile program, still a mainstay for the 
company, is awarded. 
</P>
<P>
1967: Sidewinder air-to-missile program transferred to Aeronutronic. 
</P>
<P>
1969: Air Force Satellite Control Facility established. 
</P>
<P>
1976: Name changed to Ford Aerospace Communications Corp. Intelsat V satellite 
programs awarded. 
</P>
<P>
1977: Pave Tack targeting system award. 
</P>
<P>
1978: First Goddard Space Flight Center award. 
</P>
<P>
1980: Space Telescope award. Nellis Range management contract award. 
</P>
<P>
1982: Ford Microelectronics Inc. formed. 
</P>
<P>
1984: Air Force automated remote tracking station (ARTS) award. 
</P>
<P>
1985: Sgt. York tank-mounted gun program cancelled, despite Pentagon investment 
of $1.8 billion. 1,300 Newport Beach workers laid off. 
</P>
<P>
1986: Japanese Superbird satellite award. 
</P>
<P>
1988: Corporate headquarters moved to Newport Beach. BDM International acquired 
for $425 million. 
</P>
<P>
1988: HARM low-cost seeker award. Intelsat VII award. 
</P>
<P>
1989: Loses to Martin Marietta in bidding for anti-tank weapons system that 
could be worth $3 billion. Houston mission control center upgrade award. Rumors 
begin to circulate that company may be sold. 
</P>
<P>
1990: Ford Motor Co. puts its aerospace unit up for sale on Jan. 12, saying it 
wants to focus on automotive operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
