<P>
VAN GOGH SUICIDE TIED TO VERTIGO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vincent Van Gogh was neither a lunatic nor an epileptic but suffered from a 
common inner ear disorder that led the artist to cut off his ear and eventually 
kill himself, medical experts said in a report published today. 
</P>
<P>
They said the Dutch painter, who committed suicide 100 years ago this month at 
the age of 37, had Meniere's syndrome, characterized by a painful ringing or 
buzzing in the ear and vertigo -- attacks of disabling dizziness. 
</P>
<P>
The report from the Swedish Medical Center in Englewood, Colo., was based on an 
examination of medical records and Van Gogh's letters and was published in this 
week's Journal of the American Medical Assn. 
</P>
<P>
An examination of 796 of Van Gogh's personal letters "reveals a man constantly 
in control of his reason and suffering from severe repeated attacks of 
disabling vertigo, not a seizure disorder," the study said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
